            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head/>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p>John F. Lewis our U. S. Senator, elected by and as the nominee of the
                        conservatives of the Legislature, seems to take every opportunity to exhibit
                        his ultra opposition to the Southern people. Allied actively with the ultras
                        in Congress, meddling with the elections in Washington, threatening the
                        Republicans in the Virginia Legislature, or opposing the nomination of
                        Akerman of Georgia, because he served on Toombs' staff, while he for the
                        same reason took a Confederate contract to make the iron, which dealt death
                        and destruction to the ranks of his friends, he exhibits the same ultra
                        Radicalism, and is not by any means the Representative of the sentiments of
                        the State in the U. S. Senate. His pride should induce him to relinquish the
                        position he holds and in which he must know that he misrepresents his
                        people. Has not our Legislature sufficient back-bone to request him to
                        resign?</p>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Disgusted with Senator Lewis because of his Radical views and collaboration
                    with Republicans despite being elected by conservative men. Demands he resign,
                    or the Legislature force him to resign.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>Confederate Dead</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p>On Saturday last, agreeably to announcement last week, a large number
                        repaired to the Cemetery and did much in fixing up the graves of the
                        Confederate dead buried there, while the Ladies furnished refreshments for
                        those engaged in this labor of love.</p>
                    <p>By far the greatest good accomplished was the formation of an Association for
                        fixing up and keeping in proper condition the Confederate Cemetery, as
                        published below, and invite all sympathizers throughout the county to unite
                        and act with this most commendable organization.</p>
                    <p>At a meeting of ex-Confederate soldiers and their friends, held, at the
                        Cemetery, Staunton June 18, 1870, Col. A. W. Harman was called to the chair,
                        and Capt. Charles D. McCoy, was requested to act as Secretary.</p>
                    <p>The chairman stated the object of the meeting to be the organization of a
                        permanent society for the purpose of taking proper care of the graves of our
                        comrades buried in this Cemetery.</p>
                    <p>On motion the chairman was directed to appoint a committee of five to report
                        officers for the permanent organization. This committee having retired,
                        returned and submitted the following report:</p>
                    <p>The committee appointed to report permanent officers of the Association,
                        recommend the following:</p>
                    <p>For President, Col. Jas. H. Skinner, 52nd Infantry.</p>
                    <p>For Vice Presidents, Col. Jno. B. Baldwin, Col. M. G. Harman, Col. A. W.
                        Harman, 12th Cavalry; Col H. J. Williams, 5th Infantry; Capt. W. L. Balthis,
                        Staunton Artillery; Capt. F. F. Sterrett, 14th Cavalry; Capt. E. A. Fulcher,
                        10th Cavalry; Lieut. Silas H. Walker, 1st Cavalry; Capt. F. M. Berkeley,
                        Adj't. Imboden's Brigade.</p>
                    <p>For Secretary, Capt. Chas D McCoy, 25th Infantry.</p>
                    <p>For Treasurer, Lieut. Chas S. Arnall, 5th Infantry.</p>
                    <p>For Central Executive Committee, with instructions to appoint associate
                        Committees throughout the county, and to draft articles of association for
                        the government of the society, Lt. Col Bolivar Christian, Chairman; Capt.
                        Jas. Bumgardner, 52nd Infantry; Capt. John N Opie, 6th Cavalry; Capt. Jas H.
                        Waters, 5th Infantry; S. Travers Phillips.</p>
                    <p>The Association will assemble at Staunton to receive the report of the
                        committee on the articles of association, and to perfect the organization on
                        such day as the President and Executive Committee shall appoint and publish.</p>
                    <p>R. MAUZY</p>
                    <p>B. CHRISTIAN</p>
                    <p>C. S ARNALL</p>
                    <p>W. L. BUMGARDNER</p>
                    <p>W. L. BALTHIS,(Committee)</p>
                    <p>After several motions to amend, which were all rejected, the report was
                        adopted.</p>
                    <p>The meeting then adopted a resolution requesting the Staunton papers to
                        publish these proceedings.</p>
                    <p>On motion the meeting adjourned.</p>
                    <p>A. W. CARMAN, Chairman.</p>
                    <p>CHARLES D. McCOY, Secretary.</p>
                </transcript>
